rlier editions in this National Bureau of Economic Research series, Investigations in the Economics of Aging focuses on the changing financial circumstances of the elderly and the relationship of these circumstances to health and health care. Among the topics addressed are the significance of out-of-pocket health care costs, the effects of inflation on social security, and the impact of the recent financial crisis on Americans’ well-being. Encompassing new data and advances in research methodology, the developments presented in this volume will have important implications for economies worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgingxEconomic aspectszUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aOlder peoplexHealth and hygienezUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aOlder peoplexMedical carezUnited StatesxCostsvCongresses. 0aRetireesxEconomic conditionsy21st centuryvCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aeconomy, growing old, politics, political, finance, money, wealth, income, health, wellness, relationship, end of life, research, national, investigation, financial, healthcare, social security, america, american, united states, usa, congress, retirement, retiree, 21st century, contemporary, modern, cost, hygiene, inflation, 401k, loans, elderly, cancer, disability, analysis.1 aAndreyeva, Tatiana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanks, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeshears, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhattacharya, Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandra, Amitabh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, James J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, David M., econtribu